resent)|Nissan Altima (L32)]]<br />[[Nissan Teana#J32 (2009-2013)|Nissan Teana (J32)]]\n|body_style   = 5-door [[hatchback]]<br />5-door [[station wagon|estate]]<br />2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n|engine       = '''petrol'''<br/>[[Renault K-Type engine#KxM petrol engine|1.6]] [[straight-4|I4]] [[Multi-valve|16v]]<br />[[Nissan MR engine|2.0]] I4 16v<br/>2.0[[Turbocharger|T]] I4 16v<br />[[Nissan VQ engine#VQ35DE|3.5]] [[V6 engine|V6]] 24v<br/>'''diesel'''<br/>[[Renault K-Type engine#K9K dCi|1.5 dCi]] I4 8v<br/>[[Nissan MR engine#M9R dCi|2.0 dCi]] I4 16v<br />[[V9X Engine|3.0 dCi]] V6 24v\n|transmission = 6-speed manual<br />6-speed automatic\n|wheelbase    = {{convert|2756|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|length       = {{convert|4695|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width        = {{convert|1811|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height       = {{convert|1445|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight       = {{convert|1560|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (diesel)\n|assembly     = {{ubl |South Africa: [[Rosslyn, Gauteng|Rosslyn]] ([[:de:National Car Corporation|Nissan]]; Coup\u00e9 only<!--limited to 100 units a month-->) |Pakistan: [[Karachi]] ([[Ghandhara Nissan|Nissan]], Sedan only) |France: [[Sandouville]] ([[Sandouville Renault Factory]]) |Malaysia: [[Segambut]] ([[:de:Tan Chong Euro Cars|TCEC]]; Coup\u00e9 only)}}\n}}\n\n{{Multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1 = Renault Laguna III Phase I rear.JPG\n| caption1 = Hatchback\n| image2 = 2008 Renault Latitude (X91) Dynamique dCi station wagon (17641107724).jpg\n| caption2 = Estate\n| image3 = Renault Laguna Coup\u00e9 Monaco GP dCi 150 (III) \u2013 Heckansicht, 7. Mai 2011, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg\n| caption3 = Coup\u00e9\n}}\n\n[[File:Renault Laguna 2008 Dashboard 20080122.jpg|thumb|right|Interior]]\n\nThe '''Renault Laguna III''' was officially announced in a press release on June 4, 2007. The car was unveiled to the public at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show#2007|Frankfurt Motor Show]] in September, and it went on sale in October 2007. The car comes as a five-door [[hatchback]], as a five-door [[station wagon|estate]] and a three-door [[coup\u00e9]].\n\nThis third-generation is based on the [[Nissan D platform|platform D]], shared with the [[Nissan Altima]], the [[Nissan Teana]], and the [[Nissan Murano]]. The Laguna III was the first car to have gone through the Aubevoye Technical Centre's ''Electro-Magnetic Compatibility'' unit, in the course of its development.\n\nIt was first presented as a concept car, at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show#2007|2007 Frankfurt Motor Show]], which followed some styling cues of the previous concept car, the [[Renault Fluence]]. The production version was revealed at the 2008 [[Cannes Film Festival]], coinciding with the [[Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Formula 1 Grand Prix]] to take the wraps off.\n\nThe brand new [[V6]] dCi engine delivers 235&nbsp;hp (173&nbsp;kW), while the new 3.5 litre petrol powered V6 offers 240&nbsp;hp (175&nbsp;kW). The Laguna Coup\u00e9 later appeared before the general public at the [[2008 Paris Motor Show|Paris Motor Show]] in October 2008. In January 2008, spy images of a then possible Laguna Sedan appeared on the internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/9080115.009/renault-laguna-sedan-spied |title=Renault Laguna Sedan Spied |publisher=Worldcarfans |date= |accessdate=2009-05-01}}</ref>\n\nIt was expected the car having appeared at the [[2008 Paris Motor Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/10802052427/more-renault-laguna-sedan-spy-pics|title=More Renault Laguna Sedan Spy Pics|publisher=Worldcarfans |date=2008-02-05|accessdate=2015-05-04}}</ref> However, this never made it to production. The [[Renault Latitude]] and the third generation (L43) [[Renault Samsung SM5]], which is made by [[Renault Samsung Motors]], [[South Korea]] is based on the Laguna III.\n\n===Facelift===\n{{Multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1 = Renault Laguna III facelift China 2012-05-06.JPG\n| image2 = Renault Laguna Grandtour GT dCi 180 FAP (III, Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 9. April 2011, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg\n| footer = Facelift (2010)\n}}\n\nA facelifted version of the Laguna III, called the '''Phase 2''', d\u00e9buted at the [[2010 Paris Motor Show]], and sales began in November 2010.\n\nIt has an aggressive front end compared to the older model. The range has been redesigned around six trim levels: Expression, Black Edition, Eco Business, Bose, GT 4Control and Initiale. Engine side, the only change is the engine 1.5 dCi 110&nbsp;hp, with CO2 emissions, decreased from 130 to 120g/km.\n\n===Engines===\n\n* 1.5 L (1461 cc) 8 valve dCi I4; 110&nbsp;bhp (81&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|192|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 12.1 s; 2007\u20132015\n* 1.6 L (1598 cc) 16 valve I4; 110&nbsp;bhp (81&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|192|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 11.7 s; 2007\u20132010\n* 2.0 L (1997 cc) 16 valve I4; 140&nbsp;bhp (103&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|210|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 10.1 s; 2007\u20132015\n* 2.0 L (1998 cc) 16 valve Turbo I4; 170&nbsp;bhp (125&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|220|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 9.2 s; 2007\u20132015\n* 2.0 L (1998 cc) 16 valve Turbo I4; 205&nbsp;bhp (150&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|232|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 7.8 s; 2008\u20132015\n* 2.0 L (1995 cc) 16 valve dCi I4; 130&nbsp;bhp (96&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|204|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 10.6 s; 2007\u20132015\n* 2.0 L (1995 cc) 16 valve dCi I4; 150&nbsp;bhp (110&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|210|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 9.5 s; 2007\u20132015\n* 2.0 L (1995 cc) 16 valve dCi I4; 175&nbsp;bhp (127&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|220|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 8.7 ; 2007\u20132015\n* 2.0 L (1995 cc) 16 valve dCi I4; 180&nbsp;bhp (131&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|222|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 8.5 s; 2008\u20132015\n* 3.0 L (2993 cc) 24 valve dCi V6; 235&nbsp;bhp (172&nbsp;kW); top speed: {{convert|242|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}; 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 7.3 s; 2008\u20132015\n* 3.5 L (3498 cc) 24 valve V6; 238&nbsp;bhp (175&nbsp;kW); {{convert|244|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}};&nbsp;0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h; 7.4 s; 2008\u20132015\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Successor==\nRenault was rumoured considering changing the Laguna name to Atalans for the successor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/renault/laguna/90820/2016-renault-laguna-first-glimpse-of-interior-design |title=2016 Renault Laguna: First glimpse of interior design |publisher=Auto Express |date=2015-05-13|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref> In May 2015, ''Worldcarfans'' reported the successor would premi\u00e8re on July 6, 2015, and would also replace the [[Renault Latitude|Latitude]] in the European market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/115032591084/renault-laguna-successor-could-be-unveiled-on-july |title=Renault Laguna successor could be unveiled on 6 July; coupe version axed |publisher=Worldcarfans |date=2015-03-25|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref> The coup\u00e9 version would also be discontinued, due to low demand. On 6 July 2015, Renault announced the successor will be called [[Renault Talisman|Talisman]], as part of its intention of unifying nameplates worldwide.<ref name=\"Autonews\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Renault vehicles timeline 1980 to date, Western European and North American market}}\n{{Renault}}\n\n[[Category:Renault vehicles|Laguna]]\n[[Category:Hatchbacks]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP large family cars]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Vehicles with four-wheel steering]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1993]]\n[[Category:Touring cars]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name         = Renault Laguna\n|image        = Renault Laguna Coup\u00e9 Monaco GP dCi 150 (III) \u2013 Frontansicht, 7. Mai 2011, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg\n|manufacturer = [[Renault]]\n|assembly     = {{ubl |South Africa: [[Rosslyn, Gauteng|Rosslyn]] ([[:de:National Car Corporation|Nissan]]) |Pakistan: [[Karachi]] ([[Ghandhara Nissan|Nissan]]) |France: [[Sandouville]] ([[Sandouville Renault Factory]]) |Malaysia: [[Segambut]] ([[:de:Tan Chong Euro Cars|TCEC]])}}\n|production   = 1994\u20132015\n|class        = [[Large family car]] ([[D-segment|D]])<br/>[[Coupe]]\n|predecessor  = [[Renault 21]]\n|successor    = [[Renault Talisman]]\n|layout       = [[FF layout]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Renault Laguna''' is a [[large family car]] by European standards, and was marketed by the French manufacturer [[Renault]] from 1994 to 2015. The first Laguna was launched in 1994, the second generation was launched in 2000, and the third generation was launched in October 2007.\n\nThe regular production Renault passenger models are unrelated to the [[concept car]] of the same name, the Laguna, a two-seater [[Roadster (automobile)|roadster]] presented by the automaker during the 1990 [[Paris Motor Show]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=McCosh|first=Dan|title=Automotive Newsfront|journal=Popular Science|date=January 1991|volume=237|issue=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIARsrB04zgC&pg=PA28&dq=Renault+Laguna|accessdate=24 September 2010|page=28}}</ref> The name was also previously used from 1973 to 1976 by [[Chevrolet]], for a top of the line Chevelle model, the [[Chevrolet Chevelle Laguna]].\n\nIn February 2012, Renault discontinued the Laguna, [[Renault Espace|Espace]], [[Renault Kangoo|Kangoo]], [[Renault Modus|Modus]], and [[Renault Wind|Wind]] lines in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/jobs/8966273/Renault-to-cut-five-UK-models.html|title=Renault to cut five UK models|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|date=19 December 2011}}</ref> In 2015, the Laguna was replaced by the [[Renault Talisman|Talisman]].<ref name=\"Autonews\">{{cite web |title=Renault says Talisman sedan has 'racy' design, innovative technologies |url=http://europe.autonews.com/article/20150706/ANE/150709938/renault-says-talisman-sedan-has-racy-design-innovative-technologies |work=europe.autonews.com |publisher=Automotive News Europe |accessdate=2015-07-06|date=2015-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Laguna I (1994\u20132001)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n|image      = 1997 Renault Laguna RT 2.0 Front.jpg\n|name       = Laguna I (X56)\n|production = November 1993\u20132001\n|body_style = 5-door [[hatchback]]<br />5-door [[station wagon|estate]]\n|engine     = '''petrol'''<br/>1.6 [[straight-4|I4]] [[Multi-valve|16v]]<br />1.8 I4<br />1.8 I4 16v<br />1.9 I4 16v<br />2.0 I4<br />2.0 I4 16v<br />3.0 [[V6 engine|V6]] 12v<br />'''diesel'''<br/>[[Renault F-Type engine#F9x|1.9D]] I4<br />[[Renault G-Type engine|2.2D]] I4 12v\n|assembly   = France: [[Sandouville]] <small>([[Sandouville Renault Factory]])</small>\n|length     = {{convert|4508|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width      = {{convert|1752|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height     = {{convert|1433|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight     = {{convert|1230|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (1.6 hatchback)\n|designer   = [[Patrick Le Qu\u00e9ment]] (1989)<ref>http://www.autonews.com/article/19950918000100/ANA/509180738</ref>\n}}\n\nWith development underway from 1987, design work under Patrick Le Quement began in 1988, with a final design approval in March 1989, and design freeze by the beginning of 1990. Road testing commenced in 1991 and continued from 1992 to 1993. The first generation Renault Laguna was unveiled in November 1993, and launched in January 1994, as a replacement for the [[Renault 21]], initially coming as a hatchback only.\n\nAt the [[Frankfurt Motor Show#1995|Frankfurt Motor Show]] in September 1995, an [[station wagon|estate]] version was introduced. This was known in some markets as the '''Laguna Sports Tourer''', and replaced the 21 based [[Renault 21|Renault Savanna/Nevada]]. It was initially launched as a 1.8 RN/RT, 2.0RT/RXE, and 3.0V6. A sports pack with deep front spoiler, rear spoiler, and alloy wheels was available on 2.0 versions.\n\nA limited-edition of 500 1.8RT Sport was made available in 1996, one hundred each of five colours including a metallic blue normally reserved for 2.0 models. \n\nThese limited editions sold out very quickly and so (to the annoyance of those who bought one of the original 500), the RT Sport was incorporated into the standard range at a cheaper price but having ABS, air conditioning, CD/Radio, and high-level brake light added as standard (all these were options on the more expensive, original 500). This coincided with Renault's participation in European [[Touring car]] championships.\n\nThe Laguna's equipment levels were generally much higher than the Renault 21. From launch, all models came with power steering, electric front windows, and remote central locking as standard. Most of the range had a driver's [[airbag]]. Later twin airbags, [[anti-lock braking system]], [[air-conditioning]], and a [[CD player]] became either optional extras or standard equipment.\n\nIt was given a minor update in September 1996, which included a new ''Laguna'' nameplate at the rear.\n\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" heights=\"140px\" perrow=\"2\">\nFile:1997 Renault Laguna RT 2.0 Rear.jpg|1994\u20131998 Renault Laguna (hatchback)\nFile:Renault Laguna (22037467020).jpg|1994\u20131998 Renault Laguna (estate)\nFile:Laguna1p1w.jpg|Interior\n</gallery>\n\n===Laguna Biturbo===\n\nAlso, following the pace of the [[Renault Safrane|Safrane Biturbo]], there was also a high-performance version of Laguna, named as '''Laguna Biturbo'''. However, no 4WD versions were available, as all power was transferred to the front wheels.\n\n===Engines===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:91%;\"\n|-\n!Model!!Engine type!!Displacement!!Valvetrain!!Fuel system!!Max. power at rpm!!Max. torque at rpm!!0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62 mph)!!Top speed!!Years\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" |Petrol engines\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''1.6 16v'''||[[Renault K-Type engine#K